WEBVTT

00:08.520 --> 00:12.440
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.080 --> 00:33.440
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.020 --> 00:37.760
And here are your hosts.

00:42.440 --> 00:49.500
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. British-born author James P. Hogan has
gained a reputation as one of the premier writers of hard science fiction

00:49.500 --> 00:58.960
working today. He's published seven novels so far, including Inherit the Stars,
The Gentle Giants of Ganymede, Giants' Star, Thrice Upon a Time, The Two Faces of

00:58.960 --> 01:11.120
Tomorrow, and his latest, Voyage from Yesteryear. Hogan tells us how he became
an author. When I left school when I was 16 and wanted to be a writer then, I

01:11.120 --> 01:22.780
guess it was something that I always enjoyed doing as a kid at school. You know,
the essays and the story writing exercises you get. And when I left school, I

01:22.780 --> 01:34.900
told the world I was going to be a writer. And it seemed a good idea until
somebody said, well, with all the accumulated wisdom and experience of 16 years,

01:35.060 --> 01:43.960
what are you going to write about that the world is breathlessly waiting to
hear? And I hadn't thought about that, and the answer was not a lot. So I went

01:43.960 --> 01:56.700
away into engineering and electronics and computers and things like that for
something like 20 years. And I suppose the interest in writing probably never

01:56.700 --> 02:05.500
went away. For 20 years, Hogan worked as a systems designer for computers and
sold computers to scientists for use in their research. Associating with

02:05.500 --> 02:12.540
scientists as he did, Hogan was exposed to all sorts of current scientific
research, and he would make use of his scientific contacts when he began to

02:12.540 --> 02:24.100
write seriously. I made use of my customers pretty freely as consultants, which
was kind of handy. I found that I had customers who were brain surgeons and

02:24.100 --> 02:35.460
other customers who studied pieces of rock brought back from the Apollo missions
and other guys who were investigating machine intelligence. And just about any

02:35.460 --> 02:46.840
of the topics or the favorite themes of science fiction that you could pick out
of a hat, the chances were sort of not 10 to 1 I had a customer specializing in

02:46.840 --> 02:55.440
that field. And I just had to, if I needed some background information on a
particular topic, I could almost guarantee I had a phone number in my diary of a

02:55.440 --> 03:05.100
guy who could talk all day about it. And they loved doing it as well. I used to
call them and if they'd like to come and talk to you tomorrow. Well, we're a

03:05.100 --> 03:13.240
little busy, but what's it about? Oh, I need some help with the book I'm working
on. Well, why didn't you say so? What time do you want to show up? And they talk

03:13.240 --> 03:20.360
all day. I think this is one of the interesting

03:20.360 --> 03:33.940
sides of selling computers into this kind of area. You can imagine some of these
specialists, they talk to bacteria all day long or whatever, and they end up

03:33.940 --> 03:43.680
shut in the back rooms of universities. And maybe there are four people on the
planet they can talk to who understand their language. And sometimes they find

03:43.680 --> 03:57.180
it hard to believe that somebody from the world outside that has walked in off
the street is sincerely interested to sit down and talk to them and is curious.

03:57.460 --> 04:05.420
He wants to know what they're doing. He wants to have it explained. So, writing
about his experiences with scientists, Hogan found that he was a science fiction

04:05.420 --> 04:16.700
writer. I didn't particularly set out to be a science fiction writer. I suppose
I became one by accident. I just always wanted to write and started writing

04:16.700 --> 04:25.800
stories about the little bit of life that I'd had some personal experience of
and was told I was a science fiction writer. And I said, how's that? And they

04:25.800 --> 04:33.660
said, well, the publisher is publishing it under their science fiction imprint.
So, we guess you have to be. So, I said, okay. And it kind of started out like

04:33.660 --> 04:42.320
that. Hogan's books are scientifically accurate and highly realistic. He's been
called the man who put science back into science fiction. Next time, we'll talk

04:42.320 --> 04:44.060
to James P. Hogan about some of his novels.

04:51.440 --> 04:59.160
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

04:59.160 --> 04:59.920
Odessa, Texas.

05:40.580 --> 05:44.500
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:00.100 --> 06:05.420
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:08.040 --> 06:09.740
And here are your hosts.

06:13.940 --> 06:22.140
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. James P. Hogan's 1977 science fiction
novel, Inherit the Stars, should be required reading for anyone who demands

06:22.140 --> 06:29.920
scientific accuracy in an exciting narrative. The book takes place some 50 years
in the future. A skeleton inside a space suit is found on the moon. That's

06:29.920 --> 06:38.080
interesting enough, but what follows is even more provocative. The skeleton is a
human one, and it's been on the moon for 50,000 years. The scientific unraveling

06:38.080 --> 06:48.200
of this mystery forms the basis of the novel. It's like a detective story, and
Hogan talks about the origins of the idea. 2001 was one of the factors that

06:48.200 --> 07:00.180
inspired me to write Inherit the Stars. I love the idea of something being
found, a mystery being uncovered in the course of lunar exploration that was

07:00.180 --> 07:13.320
sufficiently intriguing to motivate a lot of scientists into unraveling it. It
seemed a good opportunity to set the scientific detective story that I wanted to

07:13.320 --> 07:22.040
write. You know, okay, let's have the detective story, or the mystery that the
detectives are trying to solve, hinge around something that's turned up on the

07:22.040 --> 07:34.400
moon. Well, dead bodies are always pretty good for detective stories. It ought
to be a more interesting dead body than the standard detective thriller, so

07:34.400 --> 07:44.560
let's make it 50,000 years old and human, which raises the whole, opens up the
whole bag of worms. And let's just see how they unravel that. And I wanted the

07:44.560 --> 07:48.680
ending to be a

07:48.680 --> 07:59.160
bit of a twist, a bit of a surprise, but nevertheless plausible and rational
within the context of the story. I didn't want to bring in mystical agencies or

07:59.160 --> 08:04.000
strange

08:04.000 --> 08:13.220
laws of physics or anything like this to hold it together. The entire scientific
community of Earth starts to work on the baffling problem of the space-suited,

08:13.480 --> 08:21.620
50,000-year-old human skeleton, which they named Charlie. They soon find
remnants on the moon of Charlie's culture, a map of an unfamiliar planet, scraps

08:21.620 --> 08:29.780
of Charlie's diary in an unfamiliar language, and some technological artifacts.
With such clues, the scientists begin to piece together the incredible story of

08:29.780 --> 08:37.760
who Charlie was and why he was human. Hogan says the book sort of defines what
science is all about. It counters some of the distorted images of scientists

08:37.760 --> 08:47.060
Hogan has seen in fiction. Scientists were always eccentric and they wore odd
-colored shoes and they drew cabbages that ate people and they wanted to conquer

08:47.060 --> 08:59.100
the world or something. And there were these cute public impressions of
scientists of people who run down the street with no clothes on shouting Eureka!

09:01.400 --> 09:01.800
Or...

09:08.740 --> 09:18.360
You read phrases like, it came to him in a flash, and you read on, and what came
to him in a flash would have been enough to keep Einstein busy for the next 20

09:18.360 --> 09:32.400
years. And real science, you know, there are insights, there are strokes of
genius, but the overwhelming bulk of the work is done by a lot of unsung heroes,

09:32.580 --> 09:43.320
a lot of people doing nothing really dramatic or exciting, but just meticulously
sifting through details, collecting information for generations and for

09:43.320 --> 09:52.780
centuries, all different parts of the world. And it's really like putting
together a huge jigsaw puzzle, lots of people cutting out pieces and twisting

09:52.780 --> 10:00.380
them around. Every now and again, somebody will take a huge chunk in this corner
and see that it fits with a huge chunk down there, and that's a breakthrough.

10:00.780 --> 10:10.480
And so it goes on. And it really is a detective story. I think it's a far more
exciting one than most detective fiction. We strongly recommend you read Inherit

10:10.480 --> 10:18.020
the Stars to find out the solution to the mystery surrounding Charlie. Hogan
wrote two sequels to Inherit the Stars, and all three form a trilogy that

10:18.020 --> 10:22.800
presents an awesome view of man's origins. Next time, we'll talk with Hogan
about those other two books.

10:29.760 --> 10:37.580
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:37.580 --> 10:38.340
Odessa, Texas.

11:23.520 --> 11:27.400
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

11:43.200 --> 11:48.340
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

11:51.140 --> 11:52.640
And here are your hosts.

11:57.520 --> 12:05.340
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. James P. Hogan's science fiction novel
Inherit the Stars was popular enough with readers to justify a sequel. Two of

12:05.340 --> 12:14.380
them, in fact. The first was entitled The Gentle Giants of Ganymede, and it was
published in 1978. Hogan explains why he wrote the book. When I wrote Inherit

12:14.380 --> 12:25.960
the Stars, I had three books in mind. I had a trilogy in mind. So I put the
hooks in... Although Inherit the Stars was a complete story in itself, you know,

12:25.960 --> 12:33.580
it didn't leave anything... It didn't leave the reader hanging. It told and...
It started and told and finished a story. Nevertheless, there were a couple of

12:33.580 --> 12:47.000
hooks in there that invited some questions, which sort of, as it were, paved the
way to a follow-up book. And my thinking at the time was, I'll go that far, but

12:47.000 --> 13:00.440
I won't write the second book until I have some feedback as to how the readers
liked the first one. And I got a lot of mail, and they all liked it, and a lot

13:00.440 --> 13:09.440
of them said in their letters, will there be a follow-up? They picked out the
hooks. So I wrote The Gentle Giants. The Gentle Giants, of the title, are a race

13:09.440 --> 13:17.040
of aliens that first turned up in Inherit the Stars. In that book, scientists
from Earth had discovered a wrecked spaceship on Ganymede, one of Jupiter's huge

13:17.040 --> 13:25.020
moons. And on it were the remains of prehistoric creatures from Earth, dinosaurs
and the like. In The Gentle Giants of Ganymede, humans meet some live

13:25.020 --> 13:32.640
Ganymeans who have returned to the solar system after a mishap in space kept
them away for some 25 million years due to time dilation. It turns out that the

13:32.640 --> 13:39.780
Ganymeans had been responsible for human evolution. They'd taken primitive
hominids from Earth 25 million years ago and moved them to a planet called

13:39.780 --> 13:47.920
Minerva. Minerva was then one of the inner planets of our solar system, but it
was destroyed in a tremendous war involving the human stock that had evolved

13:47.920 --> 13:55.240
from the Ganymean experiments. The second book ends with the Ganymeans
leaving the solar system in search of their own people, who migrated from

13:55.240 --> 14:05.600
Minerva millions of years before the war that destroyed the planet. Hogan says
readers wanted a third book. And they wanted another one, and I did have a

14:05.600 --> 14:14.940
trilogy in mind when I wrote it, and the third one in that series is now
written. It's called Giant Star, and it will be, it's a July title, so it should

14:14.940 --> 14:26.680
start to appear in the bookstores around June. It's the third and last. There
won't be any more in that series. So it ties up a few of the loose ends, tells

14:26.680 --> 14:27.480
another story,

14:31.500 --> 14:41.780
continues with the characters we met in the previous two books, both the
terrestrial and the alien characters, and introduces some new ones. And I don't

14:41.780 --> 14:45.960
think there can be a fourth one, because it really, I don't think there's any
more to be said. It wraps it all up.

14:51.280 --> 14:58.860
Giant Star was published in 1981, and as Hogan said, it wraps up all the
mysteries and loose ends raised in the first two books. And it presents an

14:58.860 --> 15:07.420
absolutely breathtaking concept of man's origins, explaining also where man gets
his curious nature, his aggressiveness, and his incredible instinct for

15:07.420 --> 15:18.340
survival. Hogan talks about the underlying purpose of the whole trilogy.
Basically, it was an attempt to depict science as it is, or at least as I

15:18.340 --> 15:29.800
perceive it. And at the same time, weave that into a story that people who were
non-scientists, non-specialists, would find stimulating and arousing

15:29.800 --> 15:43.760
for the curiosity, even if, you know, without trying to turn it into a 250-page
lab report or something like that. And stimulating the books certainly are. For

15:43.760 --> 15:51.420
sheer grandeur, the whole Minervan trilogy, as some have called it, is matched
by a few other works in the field of science fiction. Isaac Asimov's Foundation

15:51.420 --> 16:00.060
trilogy comes to mind as a comparison, as does all our stapled inside John.
James P. Hogan's Inherit the Stars, The Gentle Giants of Ganymede, and Giant

16:00.060 --> 16:03.780
Star. Contemporary science fiction has little to offer that's any better.

16:10.940 --> 16:18.760
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:18.760 --> 16:19.520
Odessa, Texas.

