Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay
with us.

17:23.360 --> 17:28.560
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

17:31.300 --> 17:32.880
And here are your hosts.

17:36.980 --> 17:45.080
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Time travel is one of the traditional
themes of science fiction. One of the best, certainly one of the most realistic

17:45.080 --> 17:53.580
time travel books, is James Hogan's Thrice Upon a Time, which came out in 1980.
But for some time, for a number of years, in fact, before I wrote Thrice Upon a

17:53.580 --> 18:05.360
Time, I'd been wanting to write a time travel book for a number of reasons.
Firstly, I wanted to attempt to face up to the paradoxes, the logical paradoxes,

18:05.520 --> 18:19.380
once and for all, and answer them without cop-outs, without convenient
coincidences, and without obliging characters who just happened to do the right

18:19.380 --> 18:22.480
thing to make everything come out the way the author said.

18:26.500 --> 18:37.620
And secondly, I wanted to get away from this kind of cliche of some kind of a
conjurer's box, described or disguised as whatever, that you jump into and you

18:37.620 --> 18:39.560
jump out of and you're in some other time.

18:59.680 --> 19:09.600
Hogan wanted to avoid some of the clichés or formulas that characterized most
time travel stories. I think in too many stories, time machines are used like

19:09.600 --> 19:19.580
starships. They're just a device, a vehicle, to get some characters into an
unusual environment and then tell a pretty routine story that was stolen from

19:19.580 --> 19:29.080
Greek mythology or European medieval history. And the technology doesn't come
into the story at all. They could have gone there on a Greyhound bus. I didn't

19:29.080 --> 19:41.560
want to do that. And so the story was about some physicists who had stumbled
upon this phenomenon and had realized that if what they were seeing meant what

19:41.560 --> 19:51.560
they thought it meant, it meant that they could actually inject information into
the past and change the past, with all the questions that implies.

19:55.000 --> 20:06.000
And proceeded to test this phenomenon and obtained some very, very strange
results. The strange thing the physicists learn is that they can send messages

20:06.000 --> 20:17.480
into the past, not far into the past, maybe just 10 minutes. I didn't want it to
be a million years or a billion years or some huge span of time where really

20:17.480 --> 20:25.400
nothing that you did could make any difference. How about a lab bench
experiment? 10 minutes. You can just send a little signal back to yourself 10

20:25.400 --> 20:35.060
minutes ago and change what you've already done. This is interesting. You're
hard up against the paradoxes now. You can't find a way around them or duck

20:35.060 --> 20:44.900
them. You've got to answer the question, what happens? The logic of it, the
whole situation becomes absolutely, it drives you to the point of insanity

20:44.900 --> 20:52.860
trying to figure it out. It was the logic and the science implied by the time
travel theme that fascinated Hogan. He wanted to approach the concept

20:52.860 --> 20:59.800
realistically. And it's so realistic that you feel, after reading the book, you
could go down to Radio Shack and buy the parts to make a time travel machine.

21:00.360 --> 21:07.960
Recently, a number of responsible scientists have been speculating on the actual
possibility of time travel. We asked Hogan if he thought it would ever be a

21:07.960 --> 21:18.100
reality and if his book was meant to be prophetic. Well, I don't know whether
it's prophetic or not. Well, as is elaborated in the book itself, if something

21:18.100 --> 21:28.780
like that ever became a fact, there are some pretty interesting problems that
are going to have to be solved. And our ideas of logic and cause and effect are

21:28.780 --> 21:38.600
going to have to undergo some pretty interesting revisions. So I'm certainly not
setting myself up as a prophet and saying, yes, it'll happen. Maybe, I don't

21:38.600 --> 21:48.500
know. I think history has shown that impossible or it'll never happen are very
dangerous phrases to use in any context. More with James P. Hogan next time.

21:55.580 --> 22:03.420
